family members","Assessing germline mutations for reproductive counselling"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Eguiding selection of targeted therapy based on tumour mutations\u003C/strong\u003E. In cancer management, molecular testing identifies specific acquired genetic alterations that direct treatment decisions. For example, amplification of HER2 (ERBB2) in breast cancer or mutation of EGFR (ERBB1) in lung cancer helps clinicians select appropriate targeted therapies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEstimating lifetime cancer risk in healthy individuals\u003C/strong\u003E involves germline genetic testing for cancer predisposition genes, not analysis of acquired genetic alterations in existing tumours.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIdentifying inherited cancer predisposition syndromes\u003C/strong\u003E relates to germline genetic testing rather than acquired genetic alterations. This identifies inherited predispositions to cancer but does not guide treatment of an existing tumour.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetermining cancer risk in family members\u003C/strong\u003E involves analysis of germline mutations that may be inherited, not acquired somatic mutations specific to a tumour.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAssessing germline mutations for reproductive counselling\u003C/strong\u003E involves testing for inherited genetic variants to determine the risk of passing genetic disorders to offspring, not acquired genetic alterations in tumours.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther important indications for analysis of acquired genetic alterations in cancer management include detection of tumour-specific mutations that are hallmarks of specific cancers (e.g., BCR-ABL fusion genes in chronic myeloid leukaemia), determination of clonality as an indicator of neoplastic conditions, monitoring treatment efficacy through minimal residual disease detection, and identification of drug-resistant secondary mutations in malignancies treated with targeted therapies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Acquired genetic alterations are important diagnostic and therapeutic targets in cancer management.","Molecular testing identifies specific genetic mutations that guide selection of targeted therapies in cancer treatment.","Analysis of acquired genetic alterations helps monitor treatment response and detect minimal residual disease in malignancies."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 5, Genetic Disorders; p. 181"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79582"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20908"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79582"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-03T22:50:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-03T22:51:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13783"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96967"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10763"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Genetic disorders","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-11-21T13:05:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T13:05:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id"